         <h2>
            Our Technology
         </h2>
         <h3>
            Inertial Electrostatic Confinement
         </h3>
         <p>
            <a href="technology/index.html#iec" title="Technology - Inertial Electrostatic Confinement">IEC</a> promises a cheap, simple approach to commercial fusion power generation that could be
            developed much, much faster on a modest budget, as compared with a complex, expensive multinational project such as <a href="http://www.iter.org/" title="External Link - iter.org">ITER</a>.
         </p>
         <h3>
            Multi-pole Ion beam eXperiment
         </h3>
         <p>
            By adding a particular type of magnetic field to a traditional spherical IEC machine called <a href="technology/index.html#mix" title="Technology - Multi-pole Ion beam eXperiment">MIX</a>
            , using a shaped electromagnet which doubles as the accelerating cathode, we are able to dramatically lower the losses of energetic ions that limit the efficiency of traditional designs.
         </p>
         <h2>
            We plan to
         </h2>
         <div class="content">
            <ul>
               <li>Construct a magnetic <a href="technology/index.html#iec">IEC</a> device, called <a href="technology/index.html#mix" title="Technology - Multi-pole Ion beam eXperiment">MIX</a> for
               Multi-pole Ion beam eXperiment. Once funding is obtained construction should take no more than 12 months.
               </li>
               <li>Fully explore the fusion potential of MIX by installing several state of the art, high temperature plasma diagnostics.
               </li>
               <li>Simultaneously develop computer models which will guide us in search of the region in parameter space which maximizes fusion power, and efficiency.
               </li>
               <li>Demonstrate fusion rates consistent with fusion power output near or above break even. This should take no more than 3 years from construction.
               </li>
            </ul>
